ce:section.ce:para:
The experimental measurements of the specific surface area, average pore volume, and pore size for all the samples are listed in Table 2

                        . Upon ZIF-8 encapsulation by ZnO, the pore diameter (dp
                        ) decreases from 23.5 to 2.15 nm, falling within the mesoporous range. The specific surface area (SBET
                        ) undergoes a remarkable increase from 3.3 to 223 m2g−1, indicating a significantly expanded surface that enables the provision of additional adsorption sites. Simultaneously, the pore volume (Vp
                        ) of ZZ also experiences an augmentation from 0.019 to 0.12 cm3g−1, representing a substantial enhancement in the capacity for adsorbing gas molecules. The incorporation of Cl-CQDs during the formation of the ZZ core–shell structure led to a more open structure, as indicated by the data in Table 2. ZZCl exhibited a two-fold increase in SBET
                         compared to ZZ, along with a substantial enhancement in pore volume and a reduction in dp
                         to 1.71 nm (micropores < 2 nm). The micropores in the material play a crucial role in adsorption, suggesting that ZZCl possesses an excellent physical structure as a gas-sensitive material. As anticipated, the combination of the halogen element Cl with CQDs, introduced as a structure-directing agent into the 3D ZnO@ZIF-8 core–shell structure, controlled the morphology and surface defects of the composite material, increasing the number of active sites [58].
